Every year, consumer debt rises,

20
00:00:44,680 --> 00:00:47,130
owning a home becomes more challenging

21
00:00:47,130 --> 00:00:49,850
and everything is getting more expensive.

22
00:00:49,850 --> 00:00:52,370
This combined with supply chain shortages

23
00:00:52,370 --> 00:00:53,940
the Russian-Ukraine War,

24
00:00:53,940 --> 00:00:57,560
and an outdated school system
is a recipe for disaster.

25
00:00:57,560 --> 00:00:59,590
Let me take you back to 1902.

26
00:00:59,590 --> 00:01:02,760
When one of the richest men
in history John Rockefeller

27
00:01:02,760 --> 00:01:05,190
created the school system
as we know it today.

28
00:01:05,190 --> 00:01:06,780
As you can probably imagine

29
00:01:06,780 --> 00:01:09,870
this system wasn't created
to help people become rich

30
00:01:09,870 --> 00:01:11,720
and successful like him.

31
00:01:11,720 --> 00:01:12,930
Oh, no, no, no.

32
00:01:12,930 --> 00:01:15,960
It was invented to create
a nation of workers.

33
00:01:15,960 --> 00:01:18,390
You see, Rockefeller was an oil tycoon

34
00:01:18,390 --> 00:01:21,070
that needed an army of
people that worked hard

35
00:01:21,070 --> 00:01:22,410
and didn't ask questions.

36
00:01:22,410 --> 00:01:24,730
So what better way to achieve his goal

37
00:01:24,730 --> 00:01:27,400
than funneling kids down a controlled path

38
00:01:27,400 --> 00:01:29,400
with little individual treatment,

39
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:32,863
strict deadlines and
teachers enforcing the rules.

40
00:01:47,150 --> 00:01:48,240
When I was at this school

41
00:01:48,240 --> 00:01:50,600
I had no idea that
becoming an entrepreneur

42
00:01:50,600 --> 00:01:52,790
following my dreams was even possible.

43
00:01:52,790 --> 00:01:55,040
My teachers never really understood me

44
00:01:55,040 --> 00:01:57,640
which meant I found
school extremely boring.

45
00:01:57,640 --> 00:01:58,630
The worst thing I've always

46
00:01:58,630 --> 00:02:00,680
no one really wanted to talk about money.

47
00:02:00,680 --> 00:02:03,020
It was so taboo, after leaving this place

48
00:02:03,020 --> 00:02:04,860
I initially went down the carpentry route

49
00:02:04,860 --> 00:02:08,300
making wooden trash cans for
only a few dollars an hour.

50
00:02:08,300 --> 00:02:10,700
This probably sounds all too familiar.

51
00:02:10,700 --> 00:02:12,860
And this broken system is the main reason

52
00:02:12,860 --> 00:02:14,980
why people can't retire.

53
00:02:14,980 --> 00:02:17,780
I'm not bashing schools
or even the teachers,

54
00:02:17,780 --> 00:02:20,180
but the fact that school
still doesn't teach

55
00:02:20,180 --> 00:02:22,600
basic money management, investing,

56
00:02:22,600 --> 00:02:26,090
or even building a credit
score is just crazy to me.

57
00:02:26,090 --> 00:02:27,840
So you turn 18 and leave school

58
00:02:27,840 --> 00:02:30,220
with little understanding
of how money works

59
00:02:30,220 --> 00:02:35,220
and look for a job only to find
70% of jobs never get listed

60
00:02:35,270 --> 00:02:38,080
meaning it's not what you
know, it's who you know.

61
00:02:38,080 --> 00:02:40,940
This makes finding a job
all the more difficult,

62
00:02:40,940 --> 00:02:42,470
but none of that really matters

63
00:02:42,470 --> 00:02:44,360
because slimy credit card companies

64
00:02:44,360 --> 00:02:47,240
are putting preapproval
letters through our doors

65
00:02:47,240 --> 00:02:51,490
giving us instant access to
cash at 40% interest rates

66
00:02:51,490 --> 00:02:53,570
with no consideration of the fact

67
00:02:53,570 --> 00:02:55,440
that the majority of the population

68
00:02:55,440 --> 00:02:57,730
don't know what APR even means.

69
00:02:57,730 --> 00:03:00,310
Let load how to use a
credit card correctly.

70
00:03:00,310 --> 00:03:03,200
As you can probably tell
that really grinds my gears.

71
00:03:03,200 --> 00:03:05,770
Because of this, it's no
surprise that consumer debt

72
00:03:05,770 --> 00:03:09,490
is over $15 trillion and
rising almost every year.

73
00:03:09,490 --> 00:03:11,280
The world is changing so fast.

74
00:03:11,280 --> 00:03:14,610
That school probably couldn't
keep up even if it tried.

75
00:03:14,610 --> 00:03:17,350
Bitcoin was created in 2009,

76
00:03:17,350 --> 00:03:19,040
and it's only now becoming something

77
00:03:19,040 --> 00:03:21,330
people talk about as an investment

78
00:03:21,330 --> 00:03:23,700
even though it's been
the best performing asset

79
00:03:24,760 --> 00:03:26,300
It's very difficult to get ahead

80
00:03:26,300 --> 00:03:28,190
and save money with low income,

81
00:03:28,190 --> 00:03:31,830
especially at the moment
with 8.3% inflation

82
00:03:31,830 --> 00:03:33,950
and supply chain shortages.

83
00:03:33,950 --> 00:03:35,770
It's not a coincidence that fuel

84
00:03:35,770 --> 00:03:38,830
and utility bills are
record break in highs.

85
00:03:38,830 --> 00:03:41,520
And the people are feeling
this hit more than ever.

86
00:03:41,520 --> 00:03:43,780
So the system is clearly
rigged against you.

87
00:03:43,780 --> 00:03:46,870
However, I came from nothing and escaped.

88
00:03:46,870 --> 00:03:49,820
And so can you, this might look
like a normal train to you.

89
00:03:49,820 --> 00:03:52,220
However, this is the exact spot I sat

90
00:03:52,220 --> 00:03:54,060
when I had a revelation about money

91
00:03:54,060 --> 00:03:55,790
that would change my life forever.

92
00:03:55,790 --> 00:03:57,230
After leaving school at 16,

93
00:03:57,230 --> 00:03:59,470
I got a job as a carpenter apprentice

94
00:03:59,470 --> 00:04:02,140
that required me to commute
on the train every day.

95
00:04:02,140 --> 00:04:04,550
I remember one morning
looking around the carriage

96
00:04:04,550 --> 00:04:06,430
all the passengers, both young and old

97
00:04:06,430 --> 00:04:09,380
and I noticed they had
one thing in common.

98
00:04:09,380 --> 00:04:10,560
They all looked miserable.

99
00:04:10,560 --> 00:04:11,890
It was clear that not a soul

100
00:04:11,890 --> 00:04:13,590
was looking forward to going to work.

101
00:04:13,590 --> 00:04:16,720
It was almost like being on
a ghost train full of slaves.

102
00:04:16,720 --> 00:04:18,770
I felt sorry for them until I realized,

103
00:04:18,770 --> 00:04:21,750
I too was wearing the
same unhappy expression.

104
00:04:21,750 --> 00:04:24,560
I was one of them, but
why was I so unhappy?

105
00:04:24,560 --> 00:04:27,670
Well, it all boiled down to my finances

106
00:04:27,670 --> 00:04:29,220
although it's a very popular saying

107
00:04:29,220 --> 00:04:31,040
that money doesn't make you happy.

108
00:04:31,040 --> 00:04:32,910
I think that was probably said by someone

109
00:04:32,910 --> 00:04:34,380
that has never been broke.

110
00:04:34,380 --> 00:04:36,400
Money certainly gives you freedom.

111
00:04:36,400 --> 00:04:37,570
And the lack of freedom

112
00:04:37,570 --> 00:04:40,530
was the main reason why
all of us were so unhappy

113
00:04:40,530 --> 00:04:41,820
on the train that day.

114
00:04:41,820 --> 00:04:44,470
I was only getting paid $2 an hour.

115
00:04:44,470 --> 00:04:48,490
And from that, I had to pay $15
per week for my train ticket

116
00:04:48,490 --> 00:04:51,360
and a fair over $15 to my mum for rent.

117
00:04:51,360 --> 00:04:54,000
I had very little left
at the end of the week.

118
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:56,930
I thought to myself why
am I working so hard

119
00:04:56,930 --> 00:04:58,750
and still getting nowhere?

120
00:04:58,750 --> 00:05:01,920
Then I realized I'd taken
my eye off the ball.

121
00:05:01,920 --> 00:05:04,520
I was getting so wrapped up
in going through the motions

122
00:05:04,520 --> 00:05:06,040
and doing what I was told

123
00:05:06,040 --> 00:05:08,380
that I'd forgotten to
manage my money correctly

124
00:05:08,380 --> 00:05:10,040
and set goals.

125
00:05:10,040 --> 00:05:12,610
When people don't have
solid financial goals

126
00:05:12,610 --> 00:05:14,810
they turn into mindless zombies

127
00:05:14,810 --> 00:05:17,480
living for the weekend
and never getting ahead.

128
00:05:17,480 --> 00:05:20,460
This is when I discovered
the times 25 rule

129
00:05:20,460 --> 00:05:23,030
although it probably wasn't
called that back then.

130
00:05:23,030 --> 00:05:25,690
I pictured what my perfect
life would look like.

131
00:05:25,690 --> 00:05:27,640
And then how much money I would need

132
00:05:27,640 --> 00:05:29,280
to live like that per year.

133
00:05:29,280 --> 00:05:31,680
I then multiplied that by 25

134
00:05:31,680 --> 00:05:33,820
which gave me my freedom figure.

135
00:05:33,820 --> 00:05:36,380
This is the amount of
money I'll need saved

136
00:05:36,380 --> 00:05:37,970
so that I could fund my life

137
00:05:37,970 --> 00:05:41,610
by withdrawing 4% from
my investments per year.

138
00:05:41,610 --> 00:05:43,490
This is something everyone should do.

139
00:05:43,490 --> 00:05:45,440
As it really put things into perspective.

140
00:05:45,440 --> 00:05:48,490
For me, I became obsessed
with doing everything I could

141
00:05:48,490 --> 00:05:50,580
to make progress towards this number.

142
00:05:50,580 --> 00:05:52,590
I used to do lots of overtime.

143
00:05:52,590 --> 00:05:54,500
This is because over 12 hours

144
00:05:54,500 --> 00:05:57,290
I got paid double my usual rate.

145
00:05:57,290 --> 00:05:59,970
My friends always used to
work just a nine to five job

146
00:05:59,970 --> 00:06:01,370
and then go down the pub.

147
00:06:01,370 --> 00:06:03,910
They never desired any extra income

148
00:06:03,910 --> 00:06:05,950
as they didn't have a
solid freedom figure.

149
00:06:05,950 --> 00:06:08,900
I also started tracking all
of my income and outgoings

150
00:06:08,900 --> 00:06:10,040
with a pad and pen.

151
00:06:10,040 --> 00:06:12,270
Nowadays, there's lots of different apps

152
00:06:12,270 --> 00:06:13,330
that can help you with this,

153
00:06:13,330 --> 00:06:15,110
but here's the best part of all.

154
00:06:15,110 --> 00:06:18,870
I no longer felt like a slave
as I had a clear direction

155
00:06:18,870 --> 00:06:20,390
and an escape plan,.

156
00:06:20,390 --> 00:06:22,380
But things weren't
plain sailing from then,

157
00:06:22,380 --> 00:06:25,130
a few months later, I was
on this very roadside.

158
00:06:25,130 --> 00:06:26,840
I was head in hands realizing

159
00:06:26,840 --> 00:06:29,720
that I'd cripple myself
financially for the next year.

160
00:06:29,720 --> 00:06:32,800
You see, I was young
and I wanted a nice car.

161
00:06:32,800 --> 00:06:35,560
So I bought a green Volkswagen golf

162
00:06:35,560 --> 00:06:38,010
because everyone said
it would be a good idea.

163
00:06:38,010 --> 00:06:38,940
Don't get me wrong.

164
00:06:38,940 --> 00:06:42,070
A VW golf is a great car and I loved it.

165
00:06:42,070 --> 00:06:44,890
But the issue is I took
out a loan for the car

166
00:06:44,890 --> 00:06:47,540
which had a really high interest rate.

167
00:06:47,540 --> 00:06:51,310
This kind of purchase is
typically always a bad investment.

168
00:06:51,310 --> 00:06:53,320
I didn't care about this at the time.

169
00:06:53,320 --> 00:06:56,900
Well, until I was stood at this
rotor with a blown up engine

170
00:06:56,900 --> 00:06:58,400
this left me in a right state

171
00:06:58,400 --> 00:07:00,830
'cause I still had monthly
car payments to make.

172
00:07:00,830 --> 00:07:04,700
And now I had a $1,200 bill
on top to repair the engine.

173
00:07:04,700 --> 00:07:06,800
I'm thankful for moments like this one

174
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:08,480
as it's the hard life lessons

175
00:07:08,480 --> 00:07:11,140
that make you realize
something has to change.

176
00:07:11,140 --> 00:07:14,220
I had car loans, repair
bills, credit card debt,

177
00:07:14,220 --> 00:07:15,680
and more at the time.

178
00:07:15,680 --> 00:07:17,460
So I thought outside of the box

179
00:07:17,460 --> 00:07:19,580
and decided to use what is now known,

180
00:07:19,580 --> 00:07:21,400
as a debt avalanche method.

181
00:07:21,400 --> 00:07:23,370
The idea is, you use your paycheck

182
00:07:23,370 --> 00:07:24,770
to make the minimum payments

183
00:07:24,770 --> 00:07:27,390
on every single bit of debt you have.

184
00:07:27,390 --> 00:07:30,600
Then use the remainder of your
spare cash to pay the debt

185
00:07:30,600 --> 00:07:32,500
with the highest interest rate.

186
00:07:32,500 --> 00:07:34,120
Rinsing and repeating this method

187
00:07:34,120 --> 00:07:35,830
and taking one step at a time

188
00:07:35,830 --> 00:07:38,910
is the most effective
way to clear debt fast

189
00:07:38,910 --> 00:07:41,220
and can also save you a fortune

190
00:07:41,220 --> 00:07:43,700
by clearing the highest
interest rates first.

191
00:07:43,700 --> 00:07:46,070
It took me a whole year
of using this method

192
00:07:46,070 --> 00:07:47,550
to get back on my feet

193
00:07:47,550 --> 00:07:49,870
but I'm glad I put that chapter behind me.

194
00:07:49,870 --> 00:07:52,660
I then bumped into a man
right here in this very field

195
00:07:52,660 --> 00:07:54,790
who had changed my life forever.

196
00:07:54,790 --> 00:07:55,623
As a youngster,

197
00:07:55,623 --> 00:07:58,780
it's so easy to get
complacent about retirement.

198
00:07:58,780 --> 00:08:01,660
Look, I get it when
you're 20 or even younger

199
00:08:01,660 --> 00:08:05,120
it's not that easy to get
excited about retiring at 65.

200
00:08:05,120 --> 00:08:07,560
If that sounds like you, then don't worry.

201
00:08:07,560 --> 00:08:09,050
I was exactly the same.

202
00:08:09,050 --> 00:08:11,430
However, I was very fortunate
because the man I met

203
00:08:11,430 --> 00:08:14,220
on this model flying field
became a role model to me.

204
00:08:14,220 --> 00:08:16,220
I didn't even know he was my mentor.

205
00:08:16,220 --> 00:08:17,260
During casual chats,

206
00:08:17,260 --> 00:08:19,560
he managed to completely change my mindset

207
00:08:19,560 --> 00:08:22,670
by swapping the word retirement
with the word freedom.

208
00:08:22,670 --> 00:08:24,390
This really resonated with me

209
00:08:24,390 --> 00:08:26,300
as I've always chased freedom

210
00:08:26,300 --> 00:08:29,280
over materialistic things
like cars and drip.

211
00:08:29,280 --> 00:08:30,960
With my eyes set on freedom,

212
00:08:30,960 --> 00:08:33,530
I knew I had to begin investing long term

213
00:08:33,530 --> 00:08:35,170
and start building my wealth.

214
00:08:35,170 --> 00:08:36,750
So I opened a pension account

215
00:08:36,750 --> 00:08:39,700
and began investing 10%
of my standard wage.

216
00:08:39,700 --> 00:08:42,160
Of course, nowadays
you'd open up a Roth IRA

217
00:08:42,160 --> 00:08:45,020
if you're in the USA or
stocks and shares ISA

218
00:08:45,020 --> 00:08:46,210
if you're in the UK.

219
00:08:46,210 --> 00:08:48,060
These are essentially investing accounts

220
00:08:48,060 --> 00:08:50,230
that allow you to grow
your money over time,

221
00:08:50,230 --> 00:08:52,160
completely tax free.

222
00:08:52,160 --> 00:08:54,840
However, there are limits on
the amount you can deposit

223
00:08:54,840 --> 00:08:57,530
because otherwise they'd
just be too powerful.

224
00:08:57,530 --> 00:09:00,020
Investing 10% of my income was a huge step

225
00:09:00,020 --> 00:09:01,270
in the right direction.

226
00:09:01,270 --> 00:09:04,790
It shifted my focus towards
not only making more money

227
00:09:04,790 --> 00:09:07,340
but having my money produce more income.

228
00:09:07,340 --> 00:09:09,190
By the way, if you wanna start investing,

229
00:09:09,190 --> 00:09:12,360
then public.com are currently
giving you a free stock slice

230
00:09:12,360 --> 00:09:14,570
worth between $3 and $1000.

231
00:09:14,570 --> 00:09:16,680
When you use my link in the description

232
00:09:16,680 --> 00:09:19,890
it's a great way to kickstart
your investing journey.

233
00:09:19,890 --> 00:09:23,440
So at this point I was debt
free and I was also investing

234
00:09:23,440 --> 00:09:25,230
but I was still working every hour

235
00:09:25,230 --> 00:09:27,030
under the sun for other people,

236
00:09:27,030 --> 00:09:29,570
but I couldn't shift this niggling feeling

237
00:09:29,570 --> 00:09:31,150
that I was made for more.

238
00:09:31,150 --> 00:09:32,120
Throughout my life,

239
00:09:32,120 --> 00:09:34,580
I'd get glimpses of how
the other side lived.

240
00:09:34,580 --> 00:09:36,980
Like when I used to walk past this mansion

241
00:09:36,980 --> 00:09:38,770
on the way to school, when I was a kid

242
00:09:38,770 --> 00:09:41,670
or installing staircases
in beautiful houses

243
00:09:41,670 --> 00:09:44,080
eventually it became
just too much to ignore.

244
00:09:44,080 --> 00:09:46,360
I remember the clear breaking point

245
00:09:46,360 --> 00:09:48,920
I'd been slogging my guts out all day.

246
00:09:48,920 --> 00:09:51,260
I took a brief pause to catch my breath.

247
00:09:51,260 --> 00:09:52,980
And in that moment I looked up,

248
00:09:52,980 --> 00:09:55,460
above me I could see the senior managers

249
00:09:55,460 --> 00:09:57,210
working at their desk jobs.

250
00:09:57,210 --> 00:09:59,520
They were clearly
getting paid more than me

251
00:09:59,520 --> 00:10:02,240
but it looked like they
weren't working nearly as hard.

252
00:10:02,240 --> 00:10:04,070
That's when it hit me,
that you're not paid

253
00:10:04,070 --> 00:10:06,890
based on how much effort
you put into a job,

254
00:10:06,890 --> 00:10:10,480
be that physical or
mental, you are purely paid

255
00:10:10,480 --> 00:10:13,300
on the value that you
provide and nothing else,

256
00:10:13,300 --> 00:10:15,120
no matter how hard I worked,

257
00:10:15,120 --> 00:10:18,420
there was only so many products
I could produce in a day.

258
00:10:18,420 --> 00:10:20,610
